  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "At the wedding feast Samson said to the guests, \"I will give you a riddle. If you show it to me during the seven days of the meal (the wedding festival), and guess it, I will give you thirty sedinim (σινδόνες, tunicae, i.e., clothes worn next to the skin) and thirty changes of garments (costly dresses, that were frequently changed: see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 45:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but if ye cannot show it to me, ye shall give me the same number of garments.\" The custom or proposing riddles at banquets by way of entertainment is also to be met with among the ancient Grecians. (For proofs from Athenaeus, Pollux, Gellius, see Bochart, Hieroz. P. ii. l. ii. c. 12; and K. O. Mller, Dorier, ii. p. 392). As the guests consented to this proposal, Samson gave them the following riddle (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Judges 14:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "): \"Out of the eater came forth meat, and out of the strong came forth sweetness.\" This riddle they could not show, i.e., solve, for three days. That is to say, they occupied themselves for three days in trying to find the solution; after that they let the matter rest until the appointed term was drawing near.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
